  "title": "Identifying and Asking About Classroom Objects (Darija)",
  "dialect": "darija",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What is this?' (Masculine)"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'What is this?' for a masculine object in Darija, you say 'شنو هادا؟'. This phrase is used when the object you're asking about is considered masculine in Arabic grammar.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شنو هادا؟",
            "english": "What is this? (masculine)",
            "transliteration": "Shnu hada?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Answering 'This is...' (Masculine)"
        },
        "text": "When responding to 'شنو هادا؟', you use 'هادا...' (This is...). This structure is followed by the masculine noun.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "هادا...",
            "english": "This is... (masculine)",
            "transliteration": "Hada..."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Vocabulary: Book (Masculine)"
        },
        "text": "Let's learn our first classroom object: 'Book'. In Darija, 'book' is 'كتاب'. It's a masculine noun.",
        "examples": [
